        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="sga" resp="#NW">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><!--<milestone unit="quadrant" n="1"/>--><expan><w lemma="oróit" corresp="http://www.dil.ie/33938"><abbr>O<hi rend="supraline">R</hi></abbr><ex>ÓI</ex>T</w></expan><!--<milestone unit="quadrant" n="2"/>-->                    
                    <w lemma="do" corresp="http://www.dil.ie/17096">DO</w>
                    <lb n="2" /><!--<milestone unit="quadrant" n="3"/>--><persName><name nymRef="Degen" corresp="http://www.dil.ie/15075">D<hi rend="ligature">EG</hi><!--<milestone unit="quadrant" n="4"/>-->EN</name></persName>   
               </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                 
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>A prayer for Degen</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary"> 
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>Usually the abbreviated form of <hi rend="italic">oróit</hi> 'prayer' is marked with a suspension stroke over <hi rend="supraline">OR</hi> but here the final T is also included.</p></item>
                    <item n="2"><p><ref source="#LAW1938">Lawlor</ref> (1938, 34-5) claimed that <hi rend="italic">Degen</hi> could be identified with a bishop <hi rend="italic">Dagán</hi> of the community of Bangor (Co. Down), mentioned in Bede's <hi rend="italic">Ecclesiastical History</hi> (II.4) and also with <hi rend="italic">Daghan Inbir Dáile</hi> who's death is noted in the annals in 639AD. However, <ref source="#HAM2001">Hamlin (2001, 55)</ref> points out that <hi rend="italic">Dagán</hi> of <hi rend="italic">Inber Dáile</hi> <q>was a Leinster saint from County Wicklow</q>. <hi rend="italic">Degen</hi> of Kilconriola remains unidentified, but the vocalism could indeed point to an early date.</p></item></list>
            </div>
